{
  "$comment": "Neutral shipped <sys/stat.h> (POSIX) — the FIRST real consumer of the plan-25 PER-TARGET struct `variants` mechanism. `struct stat` has a byte layout that DIVERGES per target: glibc x86-64-linux is 144 bytes (st_nlink is a 64-bit field at offset 16; st_mode at 24, after a 4-byte __pad0 that 8-aligns st_rdev), while glibc arm64-linux is 128 bytes (st_mode at 16, st_nlink a 32-bit field at 20; st_blksize is 32-bit with a __pad2). libc's fstat() writes the REAL struct and the program reads fields at OUR offsets, so a single layout would silently corrupt data on the other arch — the variant selector picks the field list matching (arch, format). The explicit padding fields (__pad0/__pad1/__pad2/reserved) make the layout engine's natural-alignment derivation reproduce the exact glibc offsets (sizeof = 144 / 128 respectively). The nested `struct timespec` (st_atim/mtim/ctim) is FLATTENED to its two i64 components (_sec/_nsec) here — bit-identical layout (timespec is {i64,i64}, 16 bytes); the real nested-timespec field names are a c14 authoring detail. Field types are RESOLVED hir-text builtins. Gated to elf (the linux run target — the WSL FULL-UNIX-build); the arm64-macho (macOS) variant + the rest of the os_unix surface (fstat/lstat symbols, S_* constants, S_IS* macros) are the c14 follow-on. availableObjectFormats elf keeps a windows-pe `#include <sys/stat.h>` fail-loud (POSIX-on-windows is the separate os_win axis). RED-ON-DISABLE: neuter the variant selector (always variant 0) and the arm64 leg compiles the x86-64 144-byte layout → the arm64 corpus (sizeof==128) fails.",
